      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Special Levies in a Body Corporate: What Queensland Sellers Must Disclose
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A special levy is one of the most common surprises buyers encounter when purchasing a unit or townhouse. It is also one of the most predictable sources of late-campaign renegotiation for sellers who did not address it upfront.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a buyer purchases a unit or townhouse in a community titles scheme in Queensland, they are not just buying the physical lot. They are acquiring a proportional interest in the body corporate and an ongoing financial relationship with it. Part of that relationship includes liability for any special levy that has been approved by the body corporate, even if the levy was approved before the buyer's name was on the title. Understanding how special levies work, and what sellers are required to disclose about them, is essential preparation for any strata property sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a special levy is and how it differs from a standard levy</h2>
      <p>Every lot owner in a community titles scheme pays regular levies to fund the body corporate's operations. These are split between the administration fund, which covers day-to-day running costs like insurance, cleaning, and maintenance, and the sinking fund, which accumulates reserves for major capital works. Both are budgeted annually and paid quarterly or as otherwise agreed.</p>

      <p>A special levy is different. It is an extraordinary charge raised outside the normal levy cycle, to fund an expense that was not anticipated in the budget or that exceeds what the sinking fund has available. Common triggers for special levies include roof replacement, structural remediation, lift refurbishment, major painting or waterproofing works, fire safety system upgrades, and in some buildings, costs arising from building defect disputes or remediation of defective work by the original builder.</p>

      <p>Special levies are approved at a general meeting of the body corporate by a majority resolution. Once approved, all lot owners, including any new owner who takes title after the approval date, are liable to pay. This is the critical point for sellers: a buyer who settles on a lot after a special levy has been approved cannot argue they are not liable for it, even if they were not a member of the body corporate when the levy was passed. The financial liability attaches to the lot, not to the person who was the owner at the time of approval.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When sellers must disclose a special levy: approved versus under discussion</h2>
      <p>The disclosure obligation for sellers is clearest when a special levy has been formally approved by a general meeting resolution. At that point it is a known, quantified financial liability attaching to the lot and it must be included in the seller's disclosure to the buyer. A buyer who is not told about an approved special levy before settling has grounds to seek compensation or, in some circumstances, to rescind the contract.</p>

      <p>The situation is less clear when a special levy is under active discussion by the committee but has not yet been put to a general meeting. The committee may be getting quotes, canvassing options, and discussing the scope of works, without having formally proposed a specific levy amount to lot owners. Strictly speaking, an unresolved discussion is not a binding liability.</p>

      <p>In practice, however, if you know that the body corporate is actively planning works that will require a special levy, that knowledge is a material fact. A buyer who settles on a lot and then receives a notice of an upcoming special levy meeting within weeks of settlement, covering works that were well-known to the committee at the time of sale, has reasonable grounds to feel misled. The safer approach is always to disclose what you know, including the fact that works are under consideration and that a special levy may be required, rather than arguing that a formal resolution had not yet been passed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where to find the information before you list</h2>
      <p>The most reliable way to understand your building's special levy position before listing is to access the body corporate records. Under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 (Qld), lot owners are entitled to request access to the body corporate records (a Section 205 request). The records include the financial statements for both funds, the minutes of all committee and general meetings for the past several years, and any correspondence relevant to major works or disputes.</p>

      <p>Reading the minutes of the last two to three years of committee meetings and the most recent annual general meeting will tell you whether any special levy has been discussed, approved, or is in planning. Your body corporate manager can also provide a levy summary on request, which will confirm whether any special levy is currently outstanding or scheduled for payment.</p>

      <p>If your building is managed by a professional body corporate management company, a phone call to the manager will often get you the key information quickly. Ask specifically: has any special levy been approved in the past 12 months? Is there any special levy under active consideration by the committee? What is the current sinking fund balance relative to the ten-year plan? The answers to these three questions will give you a clear picture of the financial position before buyers start asking.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The disclosure statement: what the law requires</h2>
      <p>Under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act and the Property Law Act 2023 (Qld), sellers of lots in community titles schemes must provide a disclosure statement to buyers before the contract is entered into. The disclosure statement must include information about the body corporate's financial position, including the current levy amounts for both funds, whether the lot is in arrears, and any special levy in effect or approved.</p>

      <p>The disclosure certificate prepared by the body corporate manager provides the formal summary of the lot's levy position. Sellers are required to provide this to buyers, and buyers have the right to terminate the contract within 14 days of receiving it if they are not satisfied with the body corporate's financial position. Sellers who provide an accurate disclosure certificate without surprises are in a much stronger position than those whose disclosure triggers a termination or renegotiation mid-campaign.</p>

      <p>Engage your solicitor and body corporate manager early in the pre-sale process, before the listing goes live, so that the disclosure certificate can be obtained and reviewed before any buyer moves to contract. If the certificate reveals a special levy that was not expected, you and your agent can plan how to address it in the marketing and pricing rather than having it surface as a surprise during due diligence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How buyers and their solicitors respond to special levies</h2>
      <p>A buyer's solicitor who finds an approved but undisclosed special levy in the body corporate records search will almost certainly advise their client to seek a price reduction equivalent to the levy amount, or in some cases to terminate the contract. A large and unexpected levy can destabilise a campaign that was otherwise progressing well, because it changes the buyer's cost calculation at the point where they are most committed.</p>

      <p>A special levy that is disclosed upfront and accurately priced into the listing is a different matter. Buyers can factor a known levy into their offer, and sellers can present it honestly as part of the property's financial position. A building with a special levy for roof replacement, for example, may be priced slightly below comparable buildings without that levy, but the transaction can still proceed cleanly because both parties understand what they are dealing with. It is the unknown special levy discovered mid-campaign that creates the most damage, not the known and disclosed one.</p>

